value.value: Antisense RNA is RNA that is transcribed from the coding, rather than the template, strand of DNA. It is therefore complementary to mRNA.

A small RNA molecule that is the product of a longer exogenous or endogenous dsRNA, which is either a bimolecular duplex or very long hairpin, processed (via the Dicer pathway) such that numerous siRNAs accumulate from both strands of the dsRNA. siRNAs trigger the cleavage of their target molecules.
A primary transcript encoding a micro RNA.
Cytosolic LSU rRNA is an RNA component of the large subunit of cytosolic ribosomes.

definition.value: Renamed to cytosolic_LSU_rRNA from large_subunit_rRNA on 10 June 2021 as per restructuring of rRNA child terms. Updated definition to be consistent with format of other rRNA definitions. Request from EBI. See GitHub Issue #493.

value.value: An RNA transcript that does not encode for a protein rather the RNA molecule is the gene product.

definition.value: A ncRNA is a processed_transcript, so it may not contain parts such as transcribed_spacer_regions that are removed in the act of processing. For the corresponding primary_transcripts, please see term SO:0000483 nc_primary_transcript.

value.value: A region of sequence containing one or more repeat units.
An RNA synthesized on a DNA or RNA template by an RNA polymerase.

definition.value: Added relationship overlaps SO:0002300 unit_of_gene_expression with Mejia-Almonte et.al PMID:32665585 Aug 5, 2020.

value.value: A sequence_feature with an extent of zero.

definition.value: A junction is a boundary between regions. A boundary has an extent of zero.

value.value: A region (or regions) that includes all of the sequence elements necessary to encode a functional transcript. A gene may include regulatory regions, transcribed regions and/or other functional sequence regions.

definition.value: This term is mapped to MGED. Do not obsolete without consulting MGED ontology. A gene may be considered as a unit of inheritance.

value.value: A motif that is active in the DNA form of the sequence.
A region of nucleotide sequence corresponding to a known motif.

A regulatory region where transcription factor binding sites are clustered to regulate various aspects of transcription activities. (CRMs can be located a few kb to hundreds of kb upstream of the core promoter, in the coding sequence, within introns, or in the untranslated regions (UTR) sequences, and even on a different chromosome). A single gene can be regulated by multiple CRMs to give precise control of its spatial and temporal expression. CRMs function as nodes in large, intertwined regulatory network. CRM DNA accessibility is subject to regulation by dbTFs and transcription co-TFs.

definition.value: Requested by Stephen Grossmann Dec 2004. Changed relationship from has_part SO:0000235 TF_binding site to TF_binding_site is part_of SO:0000727 CRM in response to requests from GREEKC initiative in Aug 2020. Removed 3' from definition because 5' UTRs are included as well, notified by Colin Logie of GREEKC. Nov 9 2020. DS Updated name from 'CRM' to 'cis_regulatory_module' on 08 Feb 2021. See GitHub Issue #526. DS Added final sentence to definition as part of GREEKC Feb 16, 2021. See GitHub Issue #534.

value.value: A region of a chromosome.

definition.value: This is a manufactured term, that serves the purpose of allow the parts of a chromosome to have an is_a path to the root.

value.value: A region of a gene.

definition.value: A manufactured term used to allow the parts of a gene to have an is_a path to the root.

value.value: A region of a transcript.

definition.value: This term was added to provide a grouping term for the region parts of transcript, thus giving them an is_a path back to the root.

value.value: A region of a mature transcript.

definition.value: A manufactured term to collect together the parts of a mature transcript and give them an is_a path to the root.

value.value: A part of a primary transcript.

definition.value: This term was added to provide a grouping term for the region parts of primary_transcript, thus giving them an is_a path back to the root.

value.value: A region of an mRNA.

definition.value: This term was added to provide a grouping term for the region parts of mRNA, thus giving them an is_a path back to the root.

value.value: A region of UTR.

definition.value: A region of UTR. This term is a grouping term to allow the parts of UTR to have an is_a path to the root.

value.value: Biological sequence region that can be assigned to a specific subsequence of a polypeptide.

definition.value: Added to allow the polypeptide regions to have is_a paths back to the root.
A region of a gene that has a specific function.

value.value: An mRNA that is capped.
A small non coding RNA, part of a silencing system that prevents the spreading of selfish genetic elements.
A regulatory_region that modulates the transcription of a gene or genes.

definition.value: Previous parent term transcription_regulatory_region (SO:0001067) has been merged with this term on 11 Feb 2021 as part of the GREEKC consortium. See GitHub Issue #527.

value.value: A sequence motif is a short (up to 20 amino acids) region of biological interest. Such motifs, although they are too short to constitute functional domains, share sequence similarities and are conserved in different proteins. They display a common function (protein-binding, subcellular location etc.).

definition.value: Range.

value.value: A region where a transformation occurs in a protein after it has been synthesized. This which may regulate, stabilize, crosslink or introduce new chemical functionalities in the protein.

definition.value: Discrete.
A gene that codes for an RNA that can be translated into a protein.

value.value: A base is a sequence feature that corresponds to a single unit of a nucleotide polymer.
A part of an miRNA primary_transcript.
The 60-70 nucleotide region remain after Drosha processing of the primary transcript, that folds back upon itself to form a hairpin structure.

definition.value: A gene that encodes a non-coding RNA.

value.value: A region which is the result of some arbitrary experimental procedure. The procedure may be carried out with biological material or inside a computer.
A region defined by its disposition to be involved in a biological process.
A DNA region within which self-interaction occurs more often than expected by chance because of DNA-looping.
A measurable sequence feature that varies within a population.
A binding site that, in the nucleotide molecule, interacts selectively and non-covalently with polypeptide residues.

definition.value: An element that can exist within the promoter region of a gene.
Mmoved from is_a: SO:0001055 transcriptional_cis_regulatory_region as per request from GREEKC initiative in August 2020.

value.value: The minimal portion of the promoter required to properly initiate transcription in RNA polymerase II transcribed genes.
A sequence motif is a nucleotide or amino-acid sequence pattern that may have biological significance.

Histone modification is a post translationally modified region whereby residues of the histone protein are modified by methylation, acetylation, phosphorylation, ubiquitination, sumoylation, citrullination, or ADP-ribosylation.

A biological DNA region implicated in epigenomic changes caused by mechanisms other than changes in the underlying DNA sequence. This includes, nucleosomal histone post-translational modifications, nucleosome depletion to render DNA accessible and post-replicational base modifications such as cytosine modification.

definition.value: Moved from is_a biological_region (SO:0001411) to is_a regulatory_region (SO:0005836) on 11 Feb 2021. GREEKC members pointed out that this would be a more appropriate location. See GitHub Issue #530. 11 Feb 2021 updated definition along with addition of epigenomically_modified_region (SO:0002332). Epigenetically modified region is now not inherited while epigenomically modified region is not annotated as inherited. See GitHub Issue #532 and issue #534.

value.value: A conserved region within the central region of a modular centromere, where the kinetochore is formed.
A repeat region found within the modular centromere.
The inner inverted repeat region of a modular centromere and part of the central core surrounding a non-conserved central region. This region is adjacent to the central core, on each chromosome arm.
A primary transcript encoding a tasiRNA.

A non-coding RNA generally longer than 200 nucleotides that cannot be classified as any other ncRNA subtype. Similar to mRNAs, lncRNAs are mainly transcribed by RNA polymerase II, are often capped by 7-methyl guanosine at their 5' ends, polyadenylated at their 3' ends and may be spliced.

definition.value: Updated the definition of lncRNA (SO:0001877) from "A non-coding RNA over 200nucleotides in length." to "A non-coding RNA generally longer than 200 nucleotides that cannot be classified as any other ncRNA subtype. Similar to mRNAs, lncRNAs are mainly transcribed by RNA polymerase II, are often capped by 7-methyl guanosine at their 5' ends, polyadenylated at their 3' ends and may be spliced." See GitHub Issue #575

value.value: A DNA motif that is found in eukaryotic rDNA repeats, and is a site of replication fork pausing.

definition.value: Requested by Midori - June 2012.

value.value: A non-coding transcript derived from the transcript of the telomere.
A heterochromatic region of the chromosome, adjacent to the telomere (on the centromeric side) that contains repetitive DNA and sometimes genes and it is transcribed.
A primary transcript encoding a lncRNA.
